Program 3 eligibility requires that the process does not meet Program 1 requirements, has a specific SIC code, or is subject to the OSHA process safety management standard. 
For a process to fall under Program 2, it must not meet the requirements of either Program 1 or Program 3.  The facilities managed by the Public Utility fall under Program 2. 
40 CFR Part 68 is divided into the following eight subparts:
A?    Subpart A - General: This subpart discusses the scope of the RMP, states general provisions and requirements of the plan, and provides definitions;
A?    Subpart B - Hazard Assessment: This subpart discusses the offsite consequence analysis and release scenarios;
A?    Subpart C - Program 2 Prevention Program:  This subpart states the requirements of the Prevention Program for a Program 2 facility;
A?    Subpart D - Program 3 Prevention Program:  This subpart states the requirements of the Prevention Program for a Program 3 facility;
A?    Subpart E - Emergency Response: This subpart defines the emergency response program;
A?    Subpart F - Regulated Substances:  This subpart lists the substances regulated under this rule along with the threshold limits of each substance;
A?    Subpart G - Risk Management Plan: This subpart states all the information required to be submitted to the USEPA;
A?    Subpart H - Other Requirements: This subpart discusses the recordkeeping requirements of the plan.
ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM APPROACH
The Public Utility has prepared the required RMP for submission to USEPA and has implemented the plan. The facilities managed by the McAllen Public Utility fall into Program 2; therefore, this RMP consists of four parts:
A?    Management System (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart A)
A?    Hazard Assessment (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart B)
A?    Prevention Program (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart C)
A?    Emergency Response (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart E)
The RMP was developed through interviews with Cit

y of McAllen personnel, where information regarding current practices relating to the affected portions of water treatment plants was obtained.  The conditions and design adequacies of plant processes and safety equipment were assessed, and the potential for a release of a regulated substance to impact offsite areas was determined.  Sections of the completed RMP were then submitted USEPA for review and comment.  The submittal included the following:
A?    Executive Summary (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart G);
&#61485;    Offsite Consequence Analysis (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart B);
&#61485;    Five-year Accident History (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart B);
&#61485;    Program 2 Prevention Program (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart C);
&#61485;    Emergency Response Program (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart E);

A?    Data Elements;
A?    Registration (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart G);

FACILITY DESCRIPTION
Water Treatment Plant
The Southwest Water Treatment Plant (WTP) is located in McAllen, Texas, at 2501 W. Expressway 83.  Water is treated at the plant and subsequently pumped to the distribution network of pipelines, pump stations, and storage tanks.  The plant is in an urban area of town that consists of both commercial and residential development.  The plant site is entirely fenced and has two points of access. 
Chlorine Storage Area
The treatment plant consists of several buildings, including and administration building with filters, a laboratory, a main pump building, and 2 chemical buildings where chlorine is used.  Aside from the buildings, the plant has clarifiers, flocculation basins, an aerator and clearwells.  The chlorine storage area is located inside an enclosed building with a chlorine neutralizer system.
